00:00:52.330 --> 00:00:54.250
OK, so let's get moving.

00:00:54.250 --> 00:00:56.440
Last day we started talking
about polymers.

00:00:56.440 --> 00:00:57.990
These are macromolecules.

00:00:57.990 --> 00:01:01.950
Here we've got an example of a
simple compound with a double

00:01:01.950 --> 00:01:03.610
bond, vinyl chloride.

00:01:03.610 --> 00:01:08.650
And by the action of addition
polymerization, we can turn

00:01:08.650 --> 00:01:11.670
this into a macromolecule where
you see a repeat unit.

00:01:11.670 --> 00:01:15.960
The double bond has been broken
to allow but carbon to

00:01:15.960 --> 00:01:18.970
bond to another vinyl
chloride, and so on.

00:01:18.970 --> 00:01:21.530
These are very, very large
molecules, can be on the order

00:01:21.530 --> 00:01:26.690
of microns in length, mass
measured in kilodaltons, or

00:01:26.690 --> 00:01:31.290
thousands of grams per mole.

00:01:31.290 --> 00:01:33.270
So today I want to go back
and look a little

00:01:33.270 --> 00:01:34.890
bit at polymer synthesis.

00:01:34.890 --> 00:01:37.440
Then we're going to talk about
properties of polymers, and

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:40.400
end with some cultural
implications that I alluded to

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:41.510
the very beginning.

00:01:41.510 --> 00:01:45.780
So we've already seen how this
reaction begins, but let's see

00:01:45.780 --> 00:01:47.110
how it proceeds.

00:01:47.110 --> 00:01:53.230
So here's an example of starting
with an initiation

00:01:53.230 --> 00:01:57.460
reaction that generates this
hydroxyl radical that starts

00:01:57.460 --> 00:01:58.780
from a peroxide.

00:01:58.780 --> 00:02:02.560
And then you can see, in this
first instance, the unpaired

00:02:02.560 --> 00:02:05.870
electron attacks the double
bond, breaks the double bond

00:02:05.870 --> 00:02:08.770
links, and then moves that
unpaired electron to the end,

00:02:08.770 --> 00:02:10.300
and so on, and so on.

00:02:10.300 --> 00:02:14.450
So here I'm indicating that
we're going to keep attaching,

00:02:14.450 --> 00:02:17.430
in this case, ethylenes
to make polyethylene.

00:02:17.430 --> 00:02:20.210
And then at some point, we
decide that we've got the

00:02:20.210 --> 00:02:22.190
molecule long enough,
and then we have

00:02:22.190 --> 00:02:23.300
to quench the reaction.

00:02:23.300 --> 00:02:27.640
So then we add something that
will cap this unpaired

00:02:27.640 --> 00:02:31.140
electron, and this step
is called termination.

00:02:31.140 --> 00:02:34.370
So this is how we make the
long-chain molecules by this

00:02:34.370 --> 00:02:36.910
particular reaction.

00:02:36.910 --> 00:02:39.880
And the thing to know,
trivially, is that the

00:02:39.880 --> 00:02:42.040
composition of the polymer
equals the

00:02:42.040 --> 00:02:43.150
composition of the mer.

00:02:43.150 --> 00:02:44.460
You can see it right
here, that I

00:02:44.460 --> 00:02:46.090
start with vinyl chloride.

00:02:46.090 --> 00:02:48.510
Yeah, we've changed the double
bond to a single bond, but

00:02:48.510 --> 00:02:54.320
it's still C2H3Cl, C2H3Cl
taken many times.

00:02:54.320 --> 00:02:55.280
That's it.

00:02:55.280 --> 00:02:56.310
OK.

00:02:56.310 --> 00:03:00.200
There's another way
to make polymers.

00:03:00.200 --> 00:03:03.120
And this is really important,
not only in commerce, but it's

00:03:03.120 --> 00:03:04.890
most important in biology.

00:03:04.890 --> 00:03:09.370
We do not have the biological
apparatus to create radicals.

00:03:09.370 --> 00:03:13.460
So during the course of this
lecture, we have cell death

00:03:13.460 --> 00:03:15.940
proceeding in all of us,
and cell generation and

00:03:15.940 --> 00:03:20.080
polymerization reactions
occurring, amino acids being

00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:22.160
linked to form proteins
and whatnot.

00:03:22.160 --> 00:03:26.530
And that process goes by the
second mechanism, condensation

00:03:26.530 --> 00:03:27.780
polymerization.

00:03:27.780 --> 00:03:30.940
And I'll give you a simple
example of that where we start

00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:33.020
with more than one mer, OK?

00:03:33.020 --> 00:03:37.670
Involves more than
one mer type.

00:03:44.160 --> 00:03:45.830
Typically two, all right?

00:03:45.830 --> 00:03:48.340
So let's look at a reaction.

00:03:48.340 --> 00:03:52.590
So this is going to be a first
kind of a mer, and R is just a

00:03:52.590 --> 00:03:57.300
general placeholder the people
use in organic chemistry.

00:03:57.300 --> 00:04:02.300
It comes from the word residual,
but it's some giant

00:04:02.300 --> 00:04:06.700
piece of molecular mass, and
there's a hydrogen here.

00:04:06.700 --> 00:04:10.420
And this one then reacts with a
second mer, which I'm going

00:04:10.420 --> 00:04:12.010
to designate R2.

00:04:12.010 --> 00:04:13.360
And the second mer
has a hydroxyl.

00:04:16.670 --> 00:04:19.440
And what happens in condensation
polymerization,

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:25.000
is that we link R1 to R2.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:29.190
R1 is now linked to R2
in a covalent manner.

00:04:29.190 --> 00:04:39.080
And then, we take the hydrogen
and the hydroxyl, and we send

00:04:39.080 --> 00:04:40.580
them over here.

00:04:40.580 --> 00:04:43.910
So the hydrogen goes here,
the hydroxyl goes

00:04:43.910 --> 00:04:49.540
here, to form water.

00:04:49.540 --> 00:04:53.460
And this is typically conducted,
in industry, not in

00:04:53.460 --> 00:04:56.170
our bodies, but in industry,
it's typically conducted at

00:04:56.170 --> 00:05:00.240
elevated temperatures where this
eventually goes into some

00:05:00.240 --> 00:05:01.490
kind of a condenser.

00:05:04.340 --> 00:05:07.590
And then the water condenses
and makes liquid.

00:05:07.590 --> 00:05:12.000
And for this step, the
condensation step of the

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:15.810
byproduct of the reaction that
we name the process.

00:05:15.810 --> 00:05:18.390
The process isn't named
for what happens here.

00:05:18.390 --> 00:05:19.960
It's named for what
happens over here.

00:05:19.960 --> 00:05:22.690
So this is condensation
polymerization, and you can

00:05:22.690 --> 00:05:25.900
see, we have covalent linkages
at both ends, and we can add

00:05:25.900 --> 00:05:30.940
another R1H here, and then
another R2OH here, and so on,

00:05:30.940 --> 00:05:32.520
and so on, and so on.

00:05:32.520 --> 00:05:36.220
So clearly, we're losing
some of the mass of

00:05:36.220 --> 00:05:38.520
the reactants here.

00:05:38.520 --> 00:05:43.200
So the mass of the final polymer
is less than the sum

00:05:43.200 --> 00:05:47.080
of the masses of all
of the reagents.

00:05:47.080 --> 00:05:48.320
So let's make a note of that.

00:05:48.320 --> 00:05:54.770
That the mass of the polymer
formed by condensation

00:05:54.770 --> 00:06:01.730
polymerization is less than the
sum of the masses of the

00:06:01.730 --> 00:06:04.180
constituents.

00:06:04.180 --> 00:06:06.670
Or let's say reactants,
if we like.

00:06:06.670 --> 00:06:08.890
Reactants.

00:06:08.890 --> 00:06:10.140
Because we lose the
condensate.

00:06:12.790 --> 00:06:19.310
And so here's an example
from commerce.

00:06:19.310 --> 00:06:22.540
Oh, before I get to that, I
wanted to show you some of the

00:06:22.540 --> 00:06:25.600
common addition polymers,
which ones that you're

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:28.440
familiar with that are made
by this first process.

00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:29.900
So at the top, we have
polyethylene.

00:06:29.900 --> 00:06:31.400
That's we started with.

00:06:31.400 --> 00:06:36.580
And you know that's used in food
wrap, it's used in milk

00:06:36.580 --> 00:06:37.810
jugs, and so on.

00:06:37.810 --> 00:06:40.340
There's the
polytetrafluoroethylene.

00:06:40.340 --> 00:06:43.030
You remove the hydrogens, you
put fluorines, and then you

00:06:43.030 --> 00:06:44.190
make Teflon.

00:06:44.190 --> 00:06:45.740
So that's also made
by addition.

00:06:45.740 --> 00:06:48.635
Polypropylene, also
used as separator.

00:06:48.635 --> 00:06:50.910
In fact, polypropylene
is found in

00:06:50.910 --> 00:06:52.130
every lithium ion battery.

00:06:52.130 --> 00:06:55.060
It's the separator between the
two electrodes, and it's

00:06:55.060 --> 00:06:58.760
engineered so that its glass
transition temperature is

00:06:58.760 --> 00:07:02.160
about 60, 70 degrees Celsius.

00:07:02.160 --> 00:07:05.010
So that if there's some event,
and you start getting thermal

00:07:05.010 --> 00:07:08.050
runaway in your battery, and
the temperature rises to

00:07:08.050 --> 00:07:11.670
whatever, let's say the number
is 70 degrees C, the pores in

00:07:11.670 --> 00:07:14.150
the polypropylene collapse.

00:07:14.150 --> 00:07:17.380
And when they collapse, they
form a barrier, and it kills

00:07:17.380 --> 00:07:20.450
the battery, and prevents the
battery from exploding.

00:07:20.450 --> 00:07:23.550
And that's polypropylene.

00:07:23.550 --> 00:07:25.720
There's butyl rubber.

00:07:25.720 --> 00:07:26.320
What else do we have?

00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:32.610
Polystyrene, you know, which is
used in these cups and food

00:07:32.610 --> 00:07:34.080
containers.

00:07:34.080 --> 00:07:34.920
Orlon, here.

00:07:34.920 --> 00:07:38.280
Polyvinyl chloride, which is
used in everything from old

00:07:38.280 --> 00:07:42.180
vinyl phonograph records
to plumbing supplies.

00:07:42.180 --> 00:07:46.610
That white PVC tubing that's
used for piping.

00:07:46.610 --> 00:07:49.610
Polymethyl methacrylate, this
is plexiglass, which many of

00:07:49.610 --> 00:07:51.170
you are wearing in
your eyeglasses.

00:07:51.170 --> 00:07:54.530
That's this material here.

00:07:54.530 --> 00:07:55.860
Butadiene, OK.

00:07:55.860 --> 00:07:59.140
You see there's the
after-polymerization.

00:07:59.140 --> 00:08:03.450
There's still one unused double
bond, so then we can

00:08:03.450 --> 00:08:07.070
mix this later on for
cross-linking.

00:08:07.070 --> 00:08:08.630
And the various rubbers,
and so on.

00:08:08.630 --> 00:08:11.210
You can see, they all have
residual double bonds, which

00:08:11.210 --> 00:08:12.770
allows them to then participate

00:08:12.770 --> 00:08:15.460
in disulfide linkages.

00:08:15.460 --> 00:08:15.770
OK.

00:08:15.770 --> 00:08:18.240
So now here's the example I
wanted to show you that you

00:08:18.240 --> 00:08:20.040
will be familiar with
in commerce.

00:08:20.040 --> 00:08:22.910
This is the PET, the
polyethylene terephthalate,

00:08:22.910 --> 00:08:25.260
the plastic bottles.

00:08:25.260 --> 00:08:27.640
The two-liter soda bottles
are made of this stuff.

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:30.570
So you start with this thing,
which is known industrially as

00:08:30.570 --> 00:08:33.730
terephthalic acid, which
is really 1-4-benzene.

00:08:33.730 --> 00:08:36.600
You see the benzene ring here,
so one, two, three, four.

00:08:36.600 --> 00:08:39.850
So off the one position and the
four position, you have a

00:08:39.850 --> 00:08:43.420
carboxylic acid, and this
is critical in proteins.

00:08:43.420 --> 00:08:47.710
You're going to see the COOH
structure over and over again.

00:08:47.710 --> 00:08:51.110
And that H is detachable.

00:08:51.110 --> 00:08:53.660
So this, then, it becomes
a proton donor.

00:08:53.660 --> 00:08:55.820
If it's a proton donor,
it's an acid.

00:08:55.820 --> 00:09:00.210
So this is the
1-4-benzenedicarboxylic acid.

00:09:00.210 --> 00:09:03.240
And this is ethylene glycol,
which you know as the base

00:09:03.240 --> 00:09:06.150
constituent of antifreeze
for automobiles.

00:09:06.150 --> 00:09:09.480
It's really ethane with
two alcohols.

00:09:09.480 --> 00:09:10.670
So it's a diol.

00:09:10.670 --> 00:09:12.630
Ethanediol, 1-2.

00:09:12.630 --> 00:09:17.440
And you mix the ethanediol with
the terephthalic acid,

00:09:17.440 --> 00:09:21.700
spit off the proton and the
hydroxyl, leaving behind this,

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:24.480
which then forms the bridge
here, and there's the basis

00:09:24.480 --> 00:09:26.720
for the plastic soda bottle.

00:09:26.720 --> 00:09:30.140
This is the same material from
which you can make Dacron,

00:09:30.140 --> 00:09:34.290
which is a fiber used sometimes
in textiles, and

00:09:34.290 --> 00:09:39.205
Mylar, which is used in sheet
films for polymer films. So

00:09:39.205 --> 00:09:40.580
this is the PET.

00:09:40.580 --> 00:09:44.770
And note here, you see this
oxygen is acting as a bridge.

00:09:44.770 --> 00:09:47.400
It's acting as a bridge between
the terephthalic acid

00:09:47.400 --> 00:09:50.430
residual and the ethylene
glycol residual.

00:09:50.430 --> 00:09:53.430
So again, we see nature relying
on the fact that

00:09:53.430 --> 00:09:59.230
oxygen forms those two bonds and
acts as a bridge for us.

00:09:59.230 --> 00:10:00.780
OK.

00:10:00.780 --> 00:10:03.570
A couple of other
things to note.

00:10:03.570 --> 00:10:08.390
Here are the typical polymers
that are made by condensation

00:10:08.390 --> 00:10:09.040
polymerization.

00:10:09.040 --> 00:10:10.610
All of the nylons.

00:10:10.610 --> 00:10:14.750
The nylons are made by
condensation polymerization.

00:10:14.750 --> 00:10:20.360
And the bond here that exists
between the nitrogen and the

00:10:20.360 --> 00:10:22.390
carbon is called
the amide bond.

00:10:22.390 --> 00:10:26.410
Even though it's spelled A M I
D E, it's pronounced amid.

00:10:26.410 --> 00:10:27.680
So these are all nylons.

00:10:27.680 --> 00:10:29.810
The generic term
is polyamides.

00:10:29.810 --> 00:10:33.180
And you see the different
types of nylon here.

00:10:33.180 --> 00:10:38.690
Kevlar, used as a substitute
for steel belting in tires,

00:10:38.690 --> 00:10:41.910
derives its strength from this,
the benzene ring here.

00:10:41.910 --> 00:10:44.150
And polyesters, OK?

00:10:44.150 --> 00:10:46.610
The Dacron, the Mylar, I
just showed you that.

00:10:46.610 --> 00:10:47.480
Lexan.

00:10:47.480 --> 00:10:51.320
This is used in everything from
sports equipment, if you

00:10:51.320 --> 00:10:55.080
wear eyeglasses in
sports, they're

00:10:55.080 --> 00:10:56.910
probably made of Lexan.

00:10:56.910 --> 00:11:00.820
Again, look at these twin
benzene rings, and then you've

00:11:00.820 --> 00:11:03.250
got the linkage on
the end here.

00:11:03.250 --> 00:11:06.270
And also used when you're
sitting seven miles above the

00:11:06.270 --> 00:11:07.100
surface of the earth.

00:11:07.100 --> 00:11:10.460
The only thing that prevents you
from being asphyxiated or

00:11:10.460 --> 00:11:12.760
frozen to death in that
airplane is a

00:11:12.760 --> 00:11:15.010
window made of Lexan.

00:11:15.010 --> 00:11:18.990
And lastly, here are the
silicones, which are also made

00:11:18.990 --> 00:11:20.805
by condensation polymerization.

00:11:20.805 --> 00:11:23.590
And just a little note
here for you.

00:11:23.590 --> 00:11:26.910
The person who invented
the silicones

00:11:26.910 --> 00:11:28.070
didn't know his chemistry.

00:11:28.070 --> 00:11:30.410
And he thought that the
silicone, in fact, had a

00:11:30.410 --> 00:11:31.200
double bond here.

00:11:31.200 --> 00:11:33.960
See, this is acetone, and
it from comes from

00:11:33.960 --> 00:11:35.620
the family of ketones.

00:11:35.620 --> 00:11:38.840
So you have methyl above, methyl
below, carbon, and a

00:11:38.840 --> 00:11:40.220
double bond off to the side.

00:11:40.220 --> 00:11:41.970
Well, it turns out
that silicone

00:11:41.970 --> 00:11:43.420
doesn't form double bonds.

00:11:43.420 --> 00:11:45.460
Everybody in 3.091 knows this.

00:11:45.460 --> 00:11:46.750
It's too big.

00:11:46.750 --> 00:11:48.220
So it only has a single bond.

00:11:48.220 --> 00:11:50.730
If it's a single bond,
it's not an -one.

00:11:50.730 --> 00:11:54.830
It's just like a pentane,
methane, so on.

00:11:54.830 --> 00:11:57.060
So this should be a siloxane.

00:11:57.060 --> 00:12:00.630
So what people refer to as
silicones today properly are

00:12:00.630 --> 00:12:03.270
called siloxanes.

00:12:03.270 --> 00:12:03.680
OK.

00:12:03.680 --> 00:12:05.260
Another thing to note.

00:12:05.260 --> 00:12:08.010
Let's go back to the--

00:12:08.010 --> 00:12:09.820
you see here?

00:12:09.820 --> 00:12:13.170
We go down the backbone
of the nylon, there's

00:12:13.170 --> 00:12:14.450
the carboxylic acid.

00:12:14.450 --> 00:12:18.080
And there's a C with a double
bond to the O, and it spit off

00:12:18.080 --> 00:12:19.100
its H, right?

00:12:19.100 --> 00:12:20.610
That was the proton donor.

00:12:20.610 --> 00:12:21.590
Look at over here.

00:12:21.590 --> 00:12:25.100
There's an amino group here,
a nitrogen with a hydrogen.

00:12:25.100 --> 00:12:27.720
Well, if I line those
two up just right,

00:12:27.720 --> 00:12:29.100
look at what can happen.

00:12:29.100 --> 00:12:32.270
Here's a carbon-oxygen, and
here's a nitrogen-hydrogen.

00:12:32.270 --> 00:12:34.060
What do you know if you've
got hydrogen

00:12:34.060 --> 00:12:35.950
sitting next to an oxygen?

00:12:35.950 --> 00:12:37.920
It can form hydrogen bonds.

00:12:37.920 --> 00:12:42.590
And so nylons derive their
higher strength from the

00:12:42.590 --> 00:12:45.950
hydrogen bonds that form
between the chains.

00:12:45.950 --> 00:12:48.670
Doesn't this remind you
of cross-linking?

00:12:48.670 --> 00:12:50.550
It's sort of same church,
different pew.

00:12:50.550 --> 00:12:54.470
It's not as strong as a
disulfite covalent linkage,

00:12:54.470 --> 00:12:56.950
but it does form linkages.

00:12:56.950 --> 00:12:58.320
That's good.

00:12:58.320 --> 00:13:00.400
It's good because it
gives you strength.

00:13:00.400 --> 00:13:03.780
But it doesn't come with the
penalty that cross-linking

00:13:03.780 --> 00:13:04.820
comes with.

00:13:04.820 --> 00:13:05.980
And what's the penalty?

00:13:05.980 --> 00:13:09.370
You can't recycle cross- linked
polymers very easily,

00:13:09.370 --> 00:13:12.650
because you've got these
strong covalent

00:13:12.650 --> 00:13:13.750
bonds in the chains.

00:13:13.750 --> 00:13:16.750
If you heat the polymer up,
those bonds don't break.

00:13:16.750 --> 00:13:20.300
If you heat this up, the
hydrogen bonds will let go.

00:13:20.300 --> 00:13:23.930
And you can remelt nylons, you
can recycle those polymers

00:13:23.930 --> 00:13:25.260
much more easily.

00:13:25.260 --> 00:13:28.850
So I want to make another
taxonomy here that

00:13:28.850 --> 00:13:31.810
distinguishes polymers
on the basis of their

00:13:31.810 --> 00:13:33.920
ability to be recycled.

00:13:33.920 --> 00:13:36.070
Very important these days.

00:13:36.070 --> 00:13:38.620
One of the first questions
people ask if you're using a

00:13:38.620 --> 00:13:41.890
polymer in a process,
is it recyclable?

00:13:41.890 --> 00:13:43.110
And what do you do?

00:13:43.110 --> 00:13:45.750
You start thinking about the
molecular architecture in

00:13:45.750 --> 00:13:47.880
order to answer that question.

00:13:47.880 --> 00:13:48.210
OK.

00:13:48.210 --> 00:13:51.760
So let's talk about the ones
that can be recycled.

00:13:51.760 --> 00:13:54.125
So recyclable ones are called
thermoplastics.

00:14:01.040 --> 00:14:08.960
Weak van der Waals and
hydrogen bonds only.

00:14:08.960 --> 00:14:10.130
And this is between
the chains.

00:14:10.130 --> 00:14:12.750
You don't break the bonds up
and down the backbone.

00:14:12.750 --> 00:14:14.620
If you break the blinds up and
down the backbone, you'll

00:14:14.620 --> 00:14:15.910
pyrolyze the material.

00:14:15.910 --> 00:14:18.440
If you go to a high enough
temperature to break covalent

00:14:18.440 --> 00:14:22.790
bonds in the backbone of a
polymer, you're on fire.

00:14:22.790 --> 00:14:24.300
So don't go there, all right?

00:14:24.300 --> 00:14:29.710
So hydrogen bonds only, so this
can reheat and reprocess.

00:14:33.610 --> 00:14:35.810
So now we're talking about
something that's almost like

00:14:35.810 --> 00:14:36.980
recycling metal.

00:14:36.980 --> 00:14:39.300
You remelt it and reuse it.

00:14:39.300 --> 00:14:42.930
The ones that have the strong
covalent linkages are called

00:14:42.930 --> 00:14:44.180
thermal sets.

00:14:47.170 --> 00:14:49.690
And the thermal set is
difficult to recycle.

00:14:49.690 --> 00:14:50.940
This is cross-linked--

00:14:54.460 --> 00:14:55.740
difficult.

00:14:55.740 --> 00:14:57.840
Notice I'm not writing
impossible.

00:14:57.840 --> 00:15:00.570
It's difficult to recycle,
which is a polite way of

00:15:00.570 --> 00:15:02.380
saying, you can do it,
and it's really

00:15:02.380 --> 00:15:03.840
expensive to do so.

00:15:03.840 --> 00:15:05.070
You might be better off to just

00:15:05.070 --> 00:15:06.990
start with virgin material.

00:15:06.990 --> 00:15:09.410
By the way, where do we
get the material?

00:15:09.410 --> 00:15:10.500
How do we make polymers?

00:15:10.500 --> 00:15:12.890
Where do we get this
carbon from?

00:15:12.890 --> 00:15:16.420
From petroleum.

00:15:16.420 --> 00:15:18.220
You say, well, why don't
we use coal?

00:15:18.220 --> 00:15:22.170
Well, you need carbon and
hydrogen in these systems. And

00:15:22.170 --> 00:15:23.460
coal is carbon.

00:15:23.460 --> 00:15:25.240
Petroleum is hydrocarbon.

00:15:25.240 --> 00:15:27.050
So these are petroleum-derived.

00:15:27.050 --> 00:15:30.630
So all these questions about
resource utilization and so on

00:15:30.630 --> 00:15:33.210
come right up in center stage.

00:15:33.210 --> 00:15:33.470
OK.

00:15:33.470 --> 00:15:36.950
Now I want to take a few minutes
to talk about use of

00:15:36.950 --> 00:15:39.720
crystallization to strengthen
polymers, OK?

00:15:39.720 --> 00:15:48.440
So crystallization for
mechanical performance.

00:15:51.210 --> 00:15:53.350
We want to improve the
mechanical performance.

00:15:53.350 --> 00:15:54.500
And I alluded to
this last day.

00:15:54.500 --> 00:15:55.740
We;ll do this really quickly.

00:15:55.740 --> 00:16:01.050
So we've seen that if we want
to, we know that if we--

00:16:01.050 --> 00:16:02.430
let me give you the
little icon here.

00:16:02.430 --> 00:16:06.630
So you're going along like
this, and some nice, long

00:16:06.630 --> 00:16:08.490
chain, and all of a sudden,
you get a zone of

00:16:08.490 --> 00:16:09.660
crystallinity.

00:16:09.660 --> 00:16:14.390
So I'm talking about adding
crystallinity in order to

00:16:14.390 --> 00:16:15.360
strengthen the material.

00:16:15.360 --> 00:16:19.820
And so we know that this has
more bond density than the

00:16:19.820 --> 00:16:22.610
straight chain here, so this
is going to be stronger.

00:16:22.610 --> 00:16:25.270
So if I want to strengthen the
polymer, introduce more

00:16:25.270 --> 00:16:30.230
crystallization, so what
favors the onset of

00:16:30.230 --> 00:16:31.110
crystallization?

00:16:31.110 --> 00:16:32.850
Or we'll say, partial
crystallization.

00:16:32.850 --> 00:16:34.870
The whole thing doesn't
turn into a crystal.

00:16:34.870 --> 00:16:39.500
To favor crystallization, what
do we do with the various set

00:16:39.500 --> 00:16:41.370
points that we have
in the material?

00:16:41.370 --> 00:16:45.770
Well, first of all, we know with
composition, composition

00:16:45.770 --> 00:16:47.380
is one of our levers.

00:16:47.380 --> 00:16:48.630
And we want to make
it uniform.

00:16:51.120 --> 00:16:58.930
So that means homopolymer is
favored over the copolymer.

00:17:02.740 --> 00:17:05.260
Or maybe there are other
instances where you don't want

00:17:05.260 --> 00:17:05.990
crystallinity.

00:17:05.990 --> 00:17:08.420
In the soles of your running
shoe, you don't want that

00:17:08.420 --> 00:17:10.620
turning into something
that's semibrittle.

00:17:10.620 --> 00:17:11.640
You want it to be soft.

00:17:11.640 --> 00:17:14.000
So that's why we use copolymers
in the soles of

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:17.930
running shoes, in order
to disfavor.

00:17:17.930 --> 00:17:21.000
And if we want to do something
like those jewel cases that I

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:24.280
keep railing against, the jewel
cases are a homopolymer

00:17:24.280 --> 00:17:29.630
that have a fair bit
of crystallinity.

00:17:29.630 --> 00:17:33.240
The second one we talked about
last day, tacticity, this is a

00:17:33.240 --> 00:17:36.620
second lever that you have.
So we know that

00:17:36.620 --> 00:17:45.285
isotactic over atactic.

00:17:45.285 --> 00:17:48.660
The more uniform, the more
likely the material will be to

00:17:48.660 --> 00:17:49.260
crystallize.

00:17:49.260 --> 00:17:52.790
So the isotactic polystyrene
makes those jewel boxes,

00:17:52.790 --> 00:17:56.490
whereas the atactic polystyrene
makes the food

00:17:56.490 --> 00:17:58.580
containers that you get
when you buy food from

00:17:58.580 --> 00:18:00.550
the trucks out here.

00:18:00.550 --> 00:18:02.440
And number three, we talked
about conformation.

00:18:05.460 --> 00:18:07.140
And we know that
conformation--

00:18:07.140 --> 00:18:09.500
linear over branched, right?

00:18:09.500 --> 00:18:11.890
Linear over branched.

00:18:11.890 --> 00:18:15.860
If we have a branched polymer,
it's not going to pack very

00:18:15.860 --> 00:18:18.410
well, so it's less likely
to crystallize.

00:18:18.410 --> 00:18:21.170
The linear one, as I've
demonstrated in this cartoon,

00:18:21.170 --> 00:18:23.850
has a much, much higher
propensity for

00:18:23.850 --> 00:18:25.160
crystallization.

00:18:25.160 --> 00:18:25.390
All right.

00:18:25.390 --> 00:18:26.490
How about properties?

00:18:26.490 --> 00:18:29.440
Let's talk about properties.

00:18:29.440 --> 00:18:32.450
Properties of polymers.

00:18:32.450 --> 00:18:36.790
And I'm talking here about the
bulk commodity polymers.

00:18:36.790 --> 00:18:40.630
Sure, you can find specialty
polymers that have remarkable

00:18:40.630 --> 00:18:42.910
properties that aren't
characteristic of polymers,

00:18:42.910 --> 00:18:44.040
but I'm not talking
about those.

00:18:44.040 --> 00:18:45.640
So first of all.

00:18:45.640 --> 00:18:46.740
Electrical properties.

00:18:46.740 --> 00:18:49.660
They're insulators, electrical
insulators.

00:18:49.660 --> 00:18:52.160
Why are they electrical
insulators?

00:18:52.160 --> 00:18:54.970
We're talking about mainly
covalent bonds here.

00:18:54.970 --> 00:18:59.630
Covalent bonds, which means
tightly bound electrons,

00:18:59.630 --> 00:19:03.080
tightly bound and localized,
because you saw that in

00:19:03.080 --> 00:19:05.220
graphite, they're tightly
bound, but they're

00:19:05.220 --> 00:19:06.080
delocalized.

00:19:06.080 --> 00:19:08.090
So tightly bound electrons.

00:19:08.090 --> 00:19:11.230
And no ions, because we've now
recognized that we can conduct

00:19:11.230 --> 00:19:14.070
electricity not only by
electrons, but by ions.

00:19:14.070 --> 00:19:17.355
Tightly bound electrons,
no ions.

00:19:17.355 --> 00:19:21.520
That means no carriers, that
means no connectivity.

00:19:21.520 --> 00:19:22.290
Number two.

00:19:22.290 --> 00:19:24.320
What's the second property?

00:19:24.320 --> 00:19:25.790
Transparent to visible light.

00:19:32.790 --> 00:19:33.780
Again, same thing.

00:19:33.780 --> 00:19:38.880
Tightly bound electrons, not
possible to excite, et cetera.

00:19:38.880 --> 00:19:42.250
So these are clear,
and furthermore,

00:19:42.250 --> 00:19:44.800
are generally colorless.

00:19:47.410 --> 00:19:52.760
And this is especially in the
case of amorphous materials.

00:19:52.760 --> 00:19:55.700
Amorphous materials are
clear, colorless.

00:19:55.700 --> 00:19:58.290
What happens if we get
semicrystallization?

00:19:58.290 --> 00:20:01.250
Those crystalline zones, as I
showed you last day, those

00:20:01.250 --> 00:20:04.950
crystalline zones are clear and
colorless as well, but the

00:20:04.950 --> 00:20:08.880
index of refraction of the
crystalline zone is not equal

00:20:08.880 --> 00:20:12.300
to the index of refraction of
the amorphous zone, and so

00:20:12.300 --> 00:20:16.110
this boundary, if you will,
scatters light.

00:20:16.110 --> 00:20:18.550
So we have two clear and
colorless zones of different

00:20:18.550 --> 00:20:22.820
index, and so if we put them
together, we end up with

00:20:22.820 --> 00:20:29.880
something that is opaque, and
that's in the case of the

00:20:29.880 --> 00:20:30.760
crystallinity.

00:20:30.760 --> 00:20:32.040
When you have some
crystallinity,

00:20:32.040 --> 00:20:33.690
you'll give up on that.

