All right.

00:21:27.210 --> 00:21:30.200
So now, what's the third
property of polymers?

00:21:30.200 --> 00:21:31.450
Chemically inert.

00:21:33.810 --> 00:21:37.820
And this is why we use them in
food packaging, and also in

00:21:37.820 --> 00:21:40.110
other forms of packaging.

00:21:40.110 --> 00:21:45.590
Again, strong bonds, strong
covalent bonds, means that

00:21:45.590 --> 00:21:50.900
it's not very reactive with
the contents of many

00:21:50.900 --> 00:21:53.670
containers, including
foods and beverages.

00:21:53.670 --> 00:21:57.560
A fourth property that's
exploited in polymers is very

00:21:57.560 --> 00:22:00.510
low density.

00:22:00.510 --> 00:22:01.520
Why?

00:22:01.520 --> 00:22:04.290
Well, what are the constituents
of the polymers?

00:22:04.290 --> 00:22:06.970
Contains things like
carbon, nitrogen--

00:22:06.970 --> 00:22:09.170
well, let's put carbon and
hydrogen first. Those are the

00:22:09.170 --> 00:22:10.700
two biggies.

00:22:10.700 --> 00:22:14.390
So we've got carbon
and hydrogen.

00:22:14.390 --> 00:22:18.020
You saw some nitrogen, oxygen,
and then trace levels of other

00:22:18.020 --> 00:22:18.670
substances.

00:22:18.670 --> 00:22:23.530
So these are all
low Z elements.

00:22:23.530 --> 00:22:26.740
So for example, in a
beverage container.

00:22:26.740 --> 00:22:29.270
I can make a beverage
container.

00:22:29.270 --> 00:22:30.810
You see a beverage container.

00:22:30.810 --> 00:22:33.340
I see a bundle of properties.

00:22:33.340 --> 00:22:34.930
What is the bundle
of properties?

00:22:34.930 --> 00:22:38.510
It has to be some physical
rigidity, but not much,

00:22:38.510 --> 00:22:39.490
because I can squeeze this.

00:22:39.490 --> 00:22:41.170
It's OK.

00:22:41.170 --> 00:22:42.720
And it has to be chemically
inert with

00:22:42.720 --> 00:22:45.470
respect to its contents.

00:22:45.470 --> 00:22:48.560
So I could build this out
of a borosilicate

00:22:48.560 --> 00:22:50.670
glass, a glass bottle.

00:22:50.670 --> 00:22:52.210
And the density of borosilicate

00:22:52.210 --> 00:22:56.350
glass is about 3.54.

00:22:56.350 --> 00:22:58.470
Or I can make it out of
aluminum, and the density of

00:22:58.470 --> 00:23:01.270
the aluminum is about 2.7.

00:23:01.270 --> 00:23:03.340
Or I can make it out of polymer,
and the density is

00:23:03.340 --> 00:23:05.270
down close to 1.

00:23:05.270 --> 00:23:09.250
So now if I load up the beverage
truck, instead of

00:23:09.250 --> 00:23:14.530
transporting the contents plus
the mass of the container, the

00:23:14.530 --> 00:23:17.880
higher fraction now is just
the contents, and the

00:23:17.880 --> 00:23:19.630
container weighs less.

00:23:19.630 --> 00:23:22.760
When I was your age,
we had still soda

00:23:22.760 --> 00:23:24.770
cans made out of steel.

00:23:24.770 --> 00:23:26.640
Steel soda cans.

00:23:26.640 --> 00:23:26.810
Yeah.

00:23:26.810 --> 00:23:27.980
They didn't have pull tops.

00:23:27.980 --> 00:23:30.850
You had to have an opener
to open them.

00:23:30.850 --> 00:23:35.230
And the density of
steel is 7.87.

00:23:35.230 --> 00:23:36.765
Iron is 7.87.

00:23:36.765 --> 00:23:39.050
So from steel, down to this,
down to this, and so on.

00:23:39.050 --> 00:23:44.880
So you see the low density
has an advantage.

00:23:44.880 --> 00:23:47.730
But, you know, we're going to
have to go back over here and

00:23:47.730 --> 00:23:51.900
start thinking about
recyclability.

00:23:51.900 --> 00:23:56.930
So you see the balancing act
here in choosing materials.

00:23:56.930 --> 00:24:00.150
You can't just seize upon one
attribute and say, oh, this is

00:24:00.150 --> 00:24:02.550
less dense than that,
let's go with it.

00:24:02.550 --> 00:24:05.190
But it's made from petroleum,
and maybe it's not so

00:24:05.190 --> 00:24:06.780
recyclable.

00:24:06.780 --> 00:24:07.740
So now what do you do?

00:24:07.740 --> 00:24:10.490
Maybe you do make it out of
steel, because you know, what

00:24:10.490 --> 00:24:11.950
you can recycle steel.

00:24:11.950 --> 00:24:16.510
You can take the door off a 1928
Model-T Ford, melt that

00:24:16.510 --> 00:24:21.590
