00:38:54.430 --> 00:39:02.750
So I hope you've seen some
examples of how these work.

00:39:02.750 --> 00:39:04.830
So now I want to talk a
little bit about the

00:39:04.830 --> 00:39:05.900
broader societal issues.

00:39:05.900 --> 00:39:07.820
So this, I think, is sort
of a pattern of

00:39:07.820 --> 00:39:09.770
adoption of new materials.

00:39:09.770 --> 00:39:12.620
You start off with this wonder,
you know, this cool

00:39:12.620 --> 00:39:14.840
property that you get
at the lab bench.

00:39:14.840 --> 00:39:19.020
You know, when nylon was
invented, it led to

00:39:19.020 --> 00:39:19.912
democratization.

00:39:19.912 --> 00:39:24.430
Do you realize stockings,
womens' stockings, were only

00:39:24.430 --> 00:39:25.730
owned by the wealthy?

00:39:25.730 --> 00:39:26.850
Because they were
made of silk.

00:39:26.850 --> 00:39:29.550
When they were made
out of nylon, they

00:39:29.550 --> 00:39:31.590
became cheap and abundant.

00:39:31.590 --> 00:39:33.750
So that changed the way
people dressed.

00:39:33.750 --> 00:39:38.990
It changed the way people made
clothing in a way that was

00:39:38.990 --> 00:39:41.180
unimaginable before.

00:39:41.180 --> 00:39:45.790
So you could, for example, make
a billiard ball, or piano

00:39:45.790 --> 00:39:47.910
keys, without killing
an elephant.

00:39:47.910 --> 00:39:49.980
You didn't have to use ivory.

00:39:49.980 --> 00:39:52.170
You could use polymers.

00:39:52.170 --> 00:39:55.970
Huge, huge implications.

00:39:55.970 --> 00:39:59.150
So this is one of the first
commercial polymers.

00:39:59.150 --> 00:40:03.050
It's phenolic resin, and it's
made by a condensation

00:40:03.050 --> 00:40:05.070
polymerization between
carbolic acid and

00:40:05.070 --> 00:40:05.510
formaldehyde.

00:40:05.510 --> 00:40:06.960
It was called bakelite.

00:40:06.960 --> 00:40:10.120
and its corporate symbol was
B with the infinity sign.

00:40:10.120 --> 00:40:11.700
Material of a thousand uses.

00:40:11.700 --> 00:40:13.000
And this, normally, is--

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:15.290
look at the elaborate
art deco coffeepot.

00:40:15.290 --> 00:40:18.620
And this is all-- it's thermal
insulated, and so on.

00:40:18.620 --> 00:40:22.000
These are all plumbing parts
made out of bakelite, that

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:24.400
previously would be made out of
many pieces of metal that

00:40:24.400 --> 00:40:26.320
had to be machined and
fashioned together.

00:40:26.320 --> 00:40:29.780
You could take bakelite powder,
put it into a die,

00:40:29.780 --> 00:40:34.240
heat it, and out comes the part,
finished, in one step.

00:40:34.240 --> 00:40:38.420
So this has a huge implication
on productivity.

00:40:38.420 --> 00:40:42.010
But then, so now we start
talking about substitution,

00:40:42.010 --> 00:40:45.300
making the cheap things, the
piano keys, the fork here, and

00:40:45.300 --> 00:40:46.310
on and on and on.

00:40:46.310 --> 00:40:48.850
But then things that couldn't
exist before.

00:40:48.850 --> 00:40:52.440
You know, the movie film.

00:40:52.440 --> 00:40:53.580
Look at the steering
wheel here.

00:40:53.580 --> 00:40:55.350
There's the, that's indicating
the lady's

00:40:55.350 --> 00:40:58.390
stocking, and so on.

00:40:58.390 --> 00:41:01.120
This is from Look
magazine, 1940.

00:41:01.120 --> 00:41:04.270
People thought these things
were just godsends.

00:41:04.270 --> 00:41:06.130
This is Synthetica.

00:41:06.130 --> 00:41:08.470
This is a country, and it's got
the province of Cellulose,

00:41:08.470 --> 00:41:13.600
Petrolia, Castphenolic
and so on.

00:41:13.600 --> 00:41:15.430
This is the 1960s.

00:41:15.430 --> 00:41:17.740
This is plastics, the
future has arrived.

00:41:17.740 --> 00:41:19.820
It's at a museum in New York.

00:41:19.820 --> 00:41:23.350
You're looking at the interior
of a home with furniture built

00:41:23.350 --> 00:41:28.160
in, and it's all plastic walls,
and formed, and so on.

00:41:28.160 --> 00:41:30.110
I think maybe these guys were
in a drug haze or something.

00:41:30.110 --> 00:41:31.190
Those are the windows.

00:41:31.190 --> 00:41:33.230
Maybe they thought those
windows were square,

00:41:33.230 --> 00:41:35.140
rectilinear, I don't know.

00:41:35.140 --> 00:41:38.480
So this is going
way overboard.

00:41:38.480 --> 00:41:41.320
And then let me show you
a piece of iconic

00:41:41.320 --> 00:41:42.490
film from The Graduate.

00:41:42.490 --> 00:41:44.220
You'll see a young
Dustin Hoffman.

00:41:44.220 --> 00:41:46.890
He's just come back from getting
a bachelor's degree.

00:41:46.890 --> 00:41:50.030
So this could be you someday in
the not too distant future.

00:41:50.030 --> 00:41:52.350
And he's at a party that
his parents are

00:41:52.350 --> 00:41:54.404
throwing in his honor.

00:41:54.404 --> 00:41:54.891
