00:42:59.350 --> 00:42:59.530
PROFESSOR: All right.

00:42:59.530 --> 00:43:03.780
So this was 1967, '68.

00:43:03.780 --> 00:43:05.710
So what's happened since
then in plastics?

00:43:05.710 --> 00:43:08.730
Well, all of these other
considerations about

00:43:08.730 --> 00:43:13.790
recyclability, environmental
health and safety issues.

00:43:13.790 --> 00:43:16.800
In order to facilitate molding,
when you want to mold

00:43:16.800 --> 00:43:20.050
the plastic, to get those bonds
to loosen up a little

00:43:20.050 --> 00:43:23.280
bit, we use a chemical known
as a plasticizer.

00:43:23.280 --> 00:43:27.030
It's a low molecular weight
polymer that helps the--

00:43:27.030 --> 00:43:29.220
it's sort of the equivalent of
putting a little bit of olive

00:43:29.220 --> 00:43:33.080
oil in with the pasta, to give
it that freedom to move.

00:43:33.080 --> 00:43:35.910
And so this, then, when you sit
in a new car, the new car

00:43:35.910 --> 00:43:38.670
smell is the smell of the
plasticizer, which is still

00:43:38.670 --> 00:43:39.700
evaporating.

00:43:39.700 --> 00:43:42.950
And some of those plasticizers
have molecular architectures

00:43:42.950 --> 00:43:45.590
that are similar to hormones
in our bodies.

00:43:45.590 --> 00:43:49.890
And so it's not healthy for us
to be breathing this stuff.

00:43:49.890 --> 00:43:53.390
So maybe the bright future that
was talked about is not

00:43:53.390 --> 00:43:58.120
quite as bright as some people
might have thought it to be.

00:43:58.120 --> 00:43:59.480
The other thing is--

00:43:59.480 --> 00:44:01.670
you know how I showed you
the plumbing parts?

00:44:01.670 --> 00:44:03.930
Well, we started making
all kinds of

00:44:03.930 --> 00:44:07.150
things out of polymers.

00:44:07.150 --> 00:44:09.050
As a child, I remember
my father bringing

00:44:09.050 --> 00:44:11.820
me, one day, a shoe.

00:44:11.820 --> 00:44:14.890
The shoe was 100% man-made.

00:44:14.890 --> 00:44:17.290
It was all polymer.

00:44:17.290 --> 00:44:20.930
And we thought this was
the coolest thing,

00:44:20.930 --> 00:44:24.090
because of all man-made.

00:44:24.090 --> 00:44:26.200
Of course, there was a
complete reversal.

00:44:26.200 --> 00:44:29.603
People said, you know, your foot
can't breathe, and this

00:44:29.603 --> 00:44:32.280
is a silly thing to have. But
at the time, we started

00:44:32.280 --> 00:44:35.590
making-- and they were ugly.

00:44:35.590 --> 00:44:37.730
And you know, for me, if it's
ugly, I don't want to wear

00:44:37.730 --> 00:44:38.630
something that's ugly.

00:44:38.630 --> 00:44:42.680
So what happened was, we started
making all kinds of

00:44:42.680 --> 00:44:44.790
things out of polymers,
or as the public

00:44:44.790 --> 00:44:46.900
knows them, as plastics.

00:44:46.900 --> 00:44:52.110
And by the mid-'70s, to call
something plastic was to make

00:44:52.110 --> 00:44:53.990
a derogatory comment.

00:44:53.990 --> 00:44:57.620
It's plastic, it's cheap,
it's shoddy.

00:44:57.620 --> 00:45:01.350
So you know, making silk
stockings cheaper as nylon

00:45:01.350 --> 00:45:02.530
stockings was good.

00:45:02.530 --> 00:45:05.200
But if you get them too
cheap, they're cheap.

00:45:05.200 --> 00:45:05.750
See?

00:45:05.750 --> 00:45:07.030
So there's an optimum there.

00:45:07.030 --> 00:45:08.470
And all of that went
into play.

00:45:08.470 --> 00:45:10.010
By the way, how do we get
the word plastic?

00:45:10.010 --> 00:45:12.030
It comes from the
Greek plastikos.

00:45:12.030 --> 00:45:14.060
And same word as potter.

00:45:14.060 --> 00:45:15.800
So when you're working with
clay, you're working with a

00:45:15.800 --> 00:45:16.930
plastic medium.

00:45:16.930 --> 00:45:19.680
It's deformable,
it's malleable.

00:45:19.680 --> 00:45:24.240
There's Samuel Johnson "let
Thy plastick hand." So all

00:45:24.240 --> 00:45:28.180
plastics are polymers, but not
all polymers are plastics,

00:45:28.180 --> 00:45:30.980
because some polymers
can't be deformed.

00:45:30.980 --> 00:45:32.900
If they're below their glass
transition temperature,

00:45:32.900 --> 00:45:34.150
they're brittle solids.

00:45:36.780 --> 00:45:37.150
All right.

00:45:37.150 --> 00:45:40.440
So I've told you enough
about concern.

00:45:40.440 --> 00:45:42.170
Let's look at recycling.

00:45:42.170 --> 00:45:45.420
In the United States right
now, 100 billion pounds

00:45:45.420 --> 00:45:48.500
annually of polymer, 50 million
tons of which 3 to 4

00:45:48.500 --> 00:45:50.110
million are recycled.

00:45:50.110 --> 00:45:51.660
It's a very low recycle rate.

00:45:51.660 --> 00:45:54.110
So this ends up in the waste.

00:45:54.110 --> 00:45:55.950
Contrast that to steel.

00:45:55.950 --> 00:45:59.250
Steel, we still make 80 million
tons a year of virgin

00:45:59.250 --> 00:46:01.110
metal in the United States.

00:46:01.110 --> 00:46:03.300
It's still a world-class
steel industry.

00:46:03.300 --> 00:46:04.600
You can bet it's world-class.

00:46:04.600 --> 00:46:08.050
With our wages and our high
standards, if you're still in

00:46:08.050 --> 00:46:10.130
business making steel in
the United States, you

00:46:10.130 --> 00:46:12.660
better be damn good.

00:46:12.660 --> 00:46:13.900
Very good.

00:46:13.900 --> 00:46:16.920
So 80 million tons virgin
metal, 60 million tons

00:46:16.920 --> 00:46:19.310
recycled scrap.

00:46:19.310 --> 00:46:25.310
We recycle more steel per year
from automobiles than we

00:46:25.310 --> 00:46:27.830
consume building new
automobiles.

00:46:27.830 --> 00:46:29.080
It's a complete ecology.

00:46:32.020 --> 00:46:33.900
And compare that to aluminum.

00:46:33.900 --> 00:46:37.580
Aluminum, 4 million tons a year,
1 million tons recycled.

00:46:37.580 --> 00:46:41.080
Very high rate on used
beverage containers.

00:46:41.080 --> 00:46:42.210
But that's the exception.

00:46:42.210 --> 00:46:44.450
Because this was DFE, Designed
For Environment.

00:46:44.450 --> 00:46:48.570
The alloy choices were made in
order to facilitate recycling.

00:46:48.570 --> 00:46:51.280
So there were certain metals
that were forbidden to go into

00:46:51.280 --> 00:46:53.990
the alloy because
they would pose

00:46:53.990 --> 00:46:56.080
problems later in recycling.

00:46:56.080 --> 00:46:58.960
So there are many ways to get
the same deep-drawing

00:46:58.960 --> 00:46:59.760
characteristics.

00:46:59.760 --> 00:47:01.172
You know, you make a beverage
can out of a

00:47:01.172 --> 00:47:03.370
sheet, and you snap.

00:47:03.370 --> 00:47:06.050
Punch down, punch up, there's
no seam on the bottom.

00:47:06.050 --> 00:47:08.630
This is made from a single
sheet of metal.

00:47:08.630 --> 00:47:11.330
And then a second piece
comes down on the top.

00:47:11.330 --> 00:47:14.100
And so this has only aluminum,
silicon, and magnesium.

00:47:14.100 --> 00:47:17.140
You could choose other metals,
but with aluminum, silicon,

00:47:17.140 --> 00:47:20.280
magnesium, it is recyclable.

00:47:20.280 --> 00:47:22.720
But aluminum ladders-- if you're
building an airplane,

00:47:22.720 --> 00:47:25.495
let's say you're the chief
purchasing agent for Boeing.

00:47:25.495 --> 00:47:29.120
And you've got a choice of
aluminum scrap, which, you

00:47:29.120 --> 00:47:32.000
know, people might have thrown
some old fishing weights with

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:36.390
lead in there, and that's now
contaminant in the aluminum.

00:47:36.390 --> 00:47:38.800
Or you're going to buy
high-purity virgin metal, and

00:47:38.800 --> 00:47:40.330
you're going to bet the
company's future.

00:47:40.330 --> 00:47:41.630
What are you going to buy?

00:47:41.630 --> 00:47:45.050
You're going to put recycled
metal into an airplane.

00:47:45.050 --> 00:47:47.070
Have the thing fall
out of the sky.

00:47:47.070 --> 00:47:49.070
No way.

00:47:49.070 --> 00:47:50.890
So you have to be careful.

00:47:50.890 --> 00:47:54.890
Those alloys, if you take the,
I told you, the door off the

00:47:54.890 --> 00:47:59.280
1928 Model-T, and you put it
on a 2010 Taurus, you can't

00:47:59.280 --> 00:48:02.470
take the wing off a DC-3
and melt it down

00:48:02.470 --> 00:48:04.670
and put it on a 777.

00:48:04.670 --> 00:48:08.350
Because the top has an aluminum
alloy with zinc, and

00:48:08.350 --> 00:48:11.230
in the bottom one has an
aluminum alloy with copper.

00:48:11.230 --> 00:48:13.220
And if you co-melt those,
you'll end up with

00:48:13.220 --> 00:48:17.060
intermetallics, and the
alloy is unusable.

00:48:17.060 --> 00:48:18.960
So you have to separate them.

00:48:18.960 --> 00:48:20.050
Now it's not so simple.

00:48:20.050 --> 00:48:22.520
So before you go make
pronouncements saying, yeah,

00:48:22.520 --> 00:48:25.860
recycling is great,
think about it.

00:48:25.860 --> 00:48:28.530
Follow through.

00:48:28.530 --> 00:48:29.070
OK.

00:48:29.070 --> 00:48:32.990
If you find this interesting,
and the impact that polymer

00:48:32.990 --> 00:48:36.280
had on American culture, this
is a lovely book by Jeffrey

00:48:36.280 --> 00:48:40.510
Meikle on polymers
and their use.

